National top stories

  • 'He could not be moved to rise from the dining room table': Explosive hearing gives a glimpse into Trump's inaction on Jan 6

    Over seven hearings, the January 6 committee has weaved its shocking findings with surprise witness testimony, building towards the series finale, dubbed the "187 Minutes Hearing". Here's what we learned. 

  • Government looks to invoke new biosecurity powers at Australian airports as early as this afternoon

    The federal government could make foot mats mandatory for all travellers from Indonesia and create new biosecurity zones at airports in response to the foot-and-mouth disease threat.

  • Cancelled flights, delays reach record levels as airlines struggle to make comeback from COVID

    A record number of flights were cancelled or ran late last month as Australian airlines continue being pummelled by the COVID-19 pandemic and poor weather conditions.

  • Day one of Splendour in the Grass cancelled after wild weather floods festival venue

    Splendour in the Grass organisers cancel performances on day one as "significant weather event" looms off northern NSW's coast.

  • Witnesses against Ben Roberts-Smith branded 'liars, perjurers and gossips'

    Witnesses against Ben Roberts-Smith in his long-running defamation case are "liars, perjurers and gossips", a barrister tells the Federal Court in his closing address.

  • COVID-19 case numbers from around the states and territories

    Here's a quick wrap-up of Friday's COVID-19 statistics from each Australian jurisdiction.

  • As a sticky Omicron wave crashes on Australia and NZ, Jacinda Ardern is trying a different approach

    New Zealanders are required to wear masks in supermarkets and shopping malls as the country battles its second wave of Omicron infections, but experts want the government to go even further.

  • We fact checked Dominic Perrottet's claim about the flu and COVID-19 . Here's what we found

    Hospitalisation figures for COVID-19 and the flu might be vastly different, but making an assessment on which virus is worse is complicated, experts say.

  • 'You have a baby, you just put up with it': Hidden pain of birth trauma revealed in new survey

    When Amy Mageropoulos was pregnant with her first son Bobby, she dreamt about the time they'd spend together when he was born. But the reality of new motherhood is far from what she had imagined.

  • When Lynne tweeted an apology for her articles about the Taliban, her friends knew something was up

    Australian journalist Lynne O’Donnell describes three days of "cat-and-mouse" with the Taliban that eventually saw her detained for four hours.

  • Want to save money and budget better? These are the key takeaways from our finance Q&A blog

    In our Q&A blog, ABC business reporter Emily Stewart, parenting website founder Jody Allen and Financial Counselling Australia's Lody Stewart answered your budgeting and saving questions. Here are the biggest takeaways from the blog. 

  • Splendour in the Grass campers keep smiling through mud and flooding

    The water and mud are ankle deep and many tents are inundated, but it will take more than that to dampen spirits at the first Splendour since the pandemic hit. 

  • Death of Indigenous man from ear infection while in custody was preventable, inquest finds

    A coroner finds the failure to identify and treat an Indigenous inmate's ear disease precipitated the man's death in custody and recommends a trial of Medicare for Aboriginal people in custody.

  • Bookkeeper jailed for embezzling $1.5m from Australian surfing royalty Owen and Tyler Wright

    A New South Wales bookkeeper has been sentenced to more than five years in jail for embezzling $1.5 million from surfing siblings, Owen and Tyler Wright. 

  • COVID conspiracy theorist who believes he is a king twice over jailed for brutal assault on police

    Steven John Cleary, 50, will spend time behind bars for the vicious attack, which was caught on body camera. The "eruption of violence" occurred after police asked a teenager to put a mask on.

  • Cross-state cocaine bust sees nine people with alleged links to Colombian drug ring arrested

    Federal authorities have raided homes across three Australian states and territories, seizing cash and finding buckets and utes full of drugs. 

  • Why athletes at the world championships are receiving their medals early — then having them taken away

    Just seconds after a podium finish in the world championships, athletes already have their medals hung around their necks — then they have to give them back. Here's why. 

  • Elvis actor Shonka Dukureh found dead in Nashville home

    Shonka Dukureh, who played Big Mama Thornton in this year's movie about Elvis Presley, is found dead in a bedroom at her home in Nashville.

  • Cheezel saw something troubling on a footy oval 12 years ago. What he did next changed a community

    For more than a decade, one Aussie rules team in regional Victoria has ensured all players are included in the experience, no matter their abilities.

  • Cubans turn to electric scooters as fuel shortages increase

    There are now 300,000 "motorinas" in the island nation — but they're posing their own challenges. 

  • 'I didn't fit into any boxes': The gaping hole in our national conversation on domestic violence

    As women's safety ministers from across the country meet today, a key focus will be on a new, national plan to end violence against women. But there's a strong call for us to have a much more inclusive conversation about the impact of domestic violence.

  • Body recovered after man swept away by floodwaters in Nanango

    Swiftwater rescue crews are on the scene after flash flooding in Nanango and Kingaroy this morning as an east coast low causes 6-metre waves and dangerous conditions in parts of the state.

  • How aged care residents and staff are coping in the face of another COVID wave 

    For the general public, COVID-19 is something that comes in waves — but those in aged care feel constantly on edge.  

  • Puerto Rico court closes case against Ricky Martin

    A Puerto Rico court has "archived" a restraining order issued against the pop superstar.

  • Australian swimmer denies using 'banned substances' after being kicked off Comm Games team

    Isaac Cooper says he is "pretty low" after being banished from Australia's Commonwealth Games team, but says he did not take a banned substance.

  • Italy could elect its first female prime minister. Who is far right party leader Giorgia Meloni?

    The leader of the far-right Brothers of Italy party, Giorgia Meloni, is tipped to become the country’s first female prime minister.  

  • SA teenager acquitted of dangerous driving over triple fatal near Mount Gambier

    A South Australian teenager has been found not guilty of dangerous driving in a head-on crash that killed three people in the state's South East almost two years ago.

  • India elects Droupadi Murmu as first president from tribal community

    India's parliament and state legislatures choose the country's first president from its tribal communities and only the second woman to hold the largely ceremonial role.

  • 'Into the mouth of a bear': Ukrainian refugees being sent to Russia, their passports confiscated

    Under a strategy laid out in Russian government documents, some Ukrainians are being transported to Russia's Far East, closer to Japan than Ukraine, and are being warned to tell nobody they want to return home.

  • 'I'm not going to accept that this is how it ends': Māori artist says setback won't derail her musical journey

    Singer/songwriter Juran moved from the Northern Territory to Sydney to work with a manager she had landed in the Harbour City. Then that manager stopped answering her calls.

  • Paramotoring pilots strive to make it across Australia 'in one piece'

    In-flight meals might be self serve for three men in their bare bones aircraft as they attempt a feat not before seen.
